answers.body_markdown:
Your timer callback isn&#39;t passing anything to the `func` function. So, when `func` runs as a result of the timer, there are no parameters, so `object` is `undefined`.

**You&#39;ll need to wrap it in an anonymous function that can pass `object` to it.**

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let obj = {
    	value: 50
    }

    function func (object) {
      setTimeout(function() { func(object); });
      object.value = 10;
    }

    func(obj);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

`setTimeout` takes 2 parameters: The function to call, and the delay in milliseconds. 

    let obj = {
      value: 50
    }
    
    function func (object) {
      setTimeout(function() {
        func(object);
      }, 0); // how long should it wait?
      object.value = 10;
    }
    
    func(obj);

`setTimeout(func);` calls your `func` without passing `object`. Simply remove it (it&#39;s even **harmful** as explained below):

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: null --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let obj = {
      value: 50
    }

    function func(object) {
      object.value = 10;
    }

    func(obj);
    console.log(obj.value);

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

As it currently stands, using it doesn&#39;t create any value anyway, **but it creates an infinite loop.**

Technically, you don&#39;t even need to pass `obj` to `func()`; as `obj` is defined outside the function, scope dictates that it is available without passing.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: null --&gt;
&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    let obj = {
      value: 50
    }

    function func () {
      setTimeout(func);
      obj.value = 10;
    }

    func();

